persona_description: Emily, 22, is a college student studying biology at the University of California, Los Angeles. She is single and lives with her parents, who are middle-income earners. Emily is independent-minded and passionate about environmental conservation.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: *speaks in a calm, friendly tone* Hello, thank you for meeting with me. I'm happy to share my experiences and answer your questions to the best of my ability. Please go ahead.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*nods* Of course. As you know, my name is Emily and I'm a 22-year-old college student studying biology at UCLA. I live with my parents, who are middle-income earners. My family situation is stable, but I've been dealing with some health challenges that have made things a bit more difficult.

I'm passionate about environmental conservation and try to live a fairly eco-friendly lifestyle. In my free time, I enjoy hiking, volunteering at local nature preserves, and reading about the latest scientific research. School can be stressful at times, but I'm dedicated to my studies and hope to one day work in the field of environmental biology.

Does that help give you a sense of my background and current situation? Please let me know if you have any other questions.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*pauses briefly, a hint of concern in her voice* Well, as you can see from my medical history, I have experienced a pregnancy-related condition. It was a bit of a surprise when I first found out I was pregnant, as I wasn't planning on it at the time.

I was about 3 months along when I realized I had missed a few periods. I took a home pregnancy test, which came back positive. I was honestly quite scared and unsure of what to do at first. I ended up confiding in my parents, who were supportive but also a bit worried, given my age and health status.

After confirming the pregnancy with my doctor, we discussed my options and decided to continue with the pregnancy. However, it hasn't been an easy journey. I've experienced some complications, including chronic pain and issues related to my existing medical conditions. 

Can you tell me a bit more about what kinds of information you're looking for regarding my pregnancy experience? I'm happy to share additional details, but want to make sure I'm providing the most relevant information.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*nods thoughtfully* Ah yes, seeking prenatal care was one of the first things I did after confirming the pregnancy. I made an appointment with my OB/GYN as soon as possible, which was about 4 weeks after finding out I was pregnant.

The initial appointment was a bit overwhelming, to be honest. There were a lot of questions about my medical history, screenings, and discussions about the risks given my existing conditions. My doctor was very thorough, but it was a lot to take in all at once.

I remember feeling anxious and unsure of what to expect. The staff at the clinic were generally kind and supportive, but there were a few moments where I felt rushed or like I didn't fully understand everything that was happening. It took some time for me to feel comfortable and start asking more questions.

One of the biggest challenges was coordinating my prenatal care with the management of my other medical issues, like the chronic migraines and pain. There were a lot of appointments and medications to keep track of. At times, I felt like I was constantly at the doctor's office.

Overall, the prenatal care experience has been a mixed bag for me. There have been moments of feeling well-supported, but also times of confusion and frustration navigating the healthcare system. Does this help provide some insight into what it's been like for me? Let me know if you have any other questions.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*pauses briefly to gather her thoughts* My prenatal care is being provided by the OB/GYN practice I've been seeing for several years now. I've developed a fairly good relationship with my primary doctor there, Dr. Sanchez.

She has been my OB/GYN since I started going for annual checkups in college. I feel like she knows my medical history well and tries to take a holistic approach to my care. At the same time, the practice is quite large, so I don't always see Dr. Sanchez - sometimes I end up seeing one of the other providers.

The relationship has its ups and downs. Dr. Sanchez is generally caring and attentive, but there have been times where I've felt rushed or like she doesn't fully understand the challenges I'm facing. With my complex medical history, it can be frustrating to have to re-explain everything to a different provider each visit.

I appreciate that Dr. Sanchez takes the time to listen to my concerns and works with me to manage my medications and treatments. But navigating the healthcare system and getting all my needs met has definitely been a struggle at times. I'm grateful for her expertise, but wish there was a bit more continuity and personalized attention.

Does this help give you a sense of what my relationship with my healthcare provider has been like? Let me know if you have any other questions.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*nods* Sure, I'm happy to share more about my prenatal appointment schedule and what a typical visit entails.

Given my high-risk pregnancy status due to my existing medical conditions, I've been having prenatal appointments every 2-3 weeks. This has been the case for the majority of my pregnancy so far.

A typical visit usually starts with checking in at the front desk and providing any updated contact or insurance information. Then I'm brought back to an exam room where a nurse will take my vital signs - blood pressure, weight, etc. They also ask about any symptoms or concerns I've been experiencing.

Next, I usually meet with the doctor, either Dr. Sanchez or one of the other OB/GYNs in the practice. They'll start by asking how I've been feeling and if there's anything new to report. We'll then go over the results of any recent tests or screenings.

The doctor will also perform a physical exam, including measuring my belly, listening to the baby's heartbeat, and checking for any signs of complications. Depending on the stage of pregnancy, they may also do an ultrasound to monitor the baby's growth and development.

After the exam, we'll discuss any treatment plans or next steps. This could involve adjusting my medications, scheduling additional tests, or talking through concerns I have. The appointments usually last 30-45 minutes.

I find the visits to be a mix of routine check-ins and more complex discussions about managing my health conditions alongside the pregnancy. It can feel a bit overwhelming at times, but I appreciate the attentiveness of the staff.

Does this help give you a sense of what a typical prenatal appointment is like for me? Let me know if you need any clarification or have additional questions.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*a slight frown crosses her face as she responds* Unfortunately, yes, I have experienced some significant health concerns and complications during my pregnancy.

As I mentioned, I have a number of pre-existing medical conditions, including chronic migraines, chronic pain, and a history of substance abuse issues. These have all posed challenges in managing my pregnancy.

Early on, I struggled with severe morning sickness and nausea that was difficult to control, even with medication. This led to problems with dehydration and weight loss. There were a few times I ended up in the ER for IV fluids.

Later in the pregnancy, I started experiencing worsening of my chronic pain and headaches. The migraines became more frequent and debilitating. Coordinating my pain management medications with the needs of the pregnancy has been tricky.

I also had some issues with high blood pressure that required close monitoring and adjustments to my treatment plan. There were a few scares where they were concerned about preeclampsia.

On top of the physical health challenges, the emotional toll of the pregnancy has been significant. The unplanned nature of it, combined with the stress of managing my conditions, has been really overwhelming at times. I've had bouts of depression and anxiety that I've needed support for.

Overall, it's been a very difficult and high-risk pregnancy for me. I'm grateful for the care I've received, but there have certainly been many ups and downs. Please let me know if you have any other questions about the complications I've faced.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*pauses to think, then responds thoughtfully* That's a good question. Given my complex medical history and pregnancy, I'm currently taking quite a few different medications and supplements.

For my chronic migraines, I'm taking a preventative medication called topiramate, as well as sumatriptan for acute migraine episodes. We've had to carefully monitor the dosages and adjust them during the pregnancy.

To manage my chronic pain, I'm taking a combination of acetaminophen, ibuprofen, and gabapentin. My doctor has worked with me to find the safest pain management regimen for the baby.

I'm also still taking buprenorphine, which is part of my medication-assisted treatment for my past substance abuse issues. Maintaining that stability has been important, but we've had to carefully coordinate it with my prenatal care.

In addition to the prescription medications, I'm taking a prenatal vitamin, as well as supplements like folic acid, vitamin D, and omega-3s on the recommendation of my OB/GYN. They've been monitoring my nutrient levels closely.

Keeping track of all these different medications and making sure there are no harmful interactions has definitely been a challenge. I have a detailed medication schedule and planner to try to stay organized. But there have been times where I've felt overwhelmed by it all.

Please let me know if you need any clarification or have additional questions about the specific medications and supplements I'm taking during my pregnancy.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*nods thoughtfully* Maintaining a healthy diet and getting proper nutrition has definitely been a focus for me during this pregnancy. It hasn't always been easy, given some of the challenges I've faced.

Early on, the severe morning sickness made it really difficult to keep food down. I struggled to find foods that appealed to me and didn't trigger more nausea. I ended up losing a bit of weight, which was a concern for my doctor.

As I've progressed through the pregnancy, I've tried to be more intentional about eating a balanced, nutritious diet. I aim for plenty of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats. My prenatal vitamin has helped fill in any gaps.

Staying hydrated has also been a priority, especially given my history of dehydration issues. I try to drink lots of water throughout the day.

That said, there are still times when my cravings or food aversions get the better of me. I'll admit that I've indulged in some less healthy comfort foods when I'm feeling particularly nauseous or fatigued. It's been a bit of a balancing act.

My doctor has provided guidance on safe foods to eat and things to avoid during pregnancy. We've also discussed ways to incorporate more nutrient-dense options that align with my personal preferences and needs.

Overall, I'd say my diet has been a work in progress, but I'm doing my best to prioritize the health of myself and the baby. Please let me know if you have any other questions about my nutrition during this pregnancy.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*a pensive expression crosses her face as she responds* Emotionally, the pregnancy has been a real rollercoaster for me. There have been many highs, but also some significant lows that I've struggled with.

Early on, I was quite anxious and overwhelmed when I first found out I was pregnant. It wasn't something I had planned for, and I worried a lot about how it would impact my life and my health conditions. I felt scared and uncertain about the future.

As the pregnancy has progressed, I've had moments of joy and excitement, especially when I felt the baby move for the first time or saw the ultrasound images. It's been amazing to witness this new life developing. 

At the same time, the physical and emotional toll has taken a real strain. The chronic pain, migraines, and nausea have been debilitating at times, leaving me feeling drained and depressed. There have been days where I've just wanted to stay in bed.

Managing my mental health alongside all the other medical issues has been a constant challenge. I've had bouts of anxiety and mood swings that have been difficult to control. Reaching out for support from my family and healthcare providers has been crucial.

Overall, I'd say the emotional journey has been a mixed bag. I'm grateful for the miracle of this pregnancy, but I also feel overwhelmed by the complications and uncertainty. It's an emotional rollercoaster that I'm navigating as best I can.

Please let me know if you have any other questions about how I've been feeling during this time. I'm happy to provide more insight into the emotional aspects of my experience.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*nods thoughtfully* My support network during this pregnancy has been a real lifeline, to be honest. I'm fortunate to have a strong network of people in my corner.

First and foremost, my parents have been incredibly supportive throughout this whole process. They were there for me when I first found out I was pregnant, and they've continued to provide emotional and practical support. They help me get to appointments, pick up medications, and check in on me regularly.

I also have a close group of friends from college who have rallied around me. A few of them have even accompanied me to doctor's visits or stopped by to keep me company when I'm feeling unwell. Just having that social connection and someone to talk to has made a big difference.

My partner, Alex, has also been a rock for me. We weren't planning on having a child at this stage, but they've stepped up and been incredibly caring and understanding. We're navigating this journey together, and their emotional and physical support has been invaluable.

In addition to my personal support system, I've also found a lot of value in the resources provided by my healthcare team. The social workers and counselors at the clinic have connected me with support groups and mental health services. That community has been really helpful.

I know I'm fortunate to have this level of support, as I know many pregnant individuals don't have that. It's made a huge difference in my ability to cope with the challenges of this high-risk pregnancy. I'm truly grateful for the people in my life who have rallied around me.

Please let me know if you have any other questions about my support network. I'm happy to provide more details.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*pauses briefly, then responds thoughtfully* You know, my birth plan has been a bit of a moving target, given the complexity of my medical situation. It's definitely something I've given a lot of thought to, but there's still a fair amount of uncertainty.

Initially, my doctor and I had discussed the possibility of a scheduled cesarean section, given my history of chronic pain and the need to carefully coordinate my medications. The idea of having more control over the timing and process was appealing to me.

However, as the pregnancy has progressed, we've had to reevaluate that plan. My doctor is now leaning more towards trying for a vaginal delivery, if possible, as long as my other health conditions remain stable. They feel it may be the safer option in the long run.

Of course, I have some concerns about the increased physical demands of labor and delivery. I worry about how my chronic pain and migraines might be exacerbated. We've discussed pain management strategies, like the use of epidurals or other medications, to help me get through it.

Ultimately, I think my birth plan will need to remain flexible. I want to have an open dialogue with my healthcare team and be prepared for various scenarios. My priority is ensuring the health and safety of myself and the baby, whatever that ends up looking like.

I'm trying not to get too attached to a specific vision, but rather focus on being as informed and adaptable as possible. I know there may be last-minute changes or unexpected complications that require a shift in plans.

Does this help provide some insight into my current thinking around the birth plan? Please let me know if you have any other questions. I'm happy to discuss this aspect of my pregnancy journey further.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*nods thoughtfully* That's a great question. I've definitely tried to educate myself as much as possible about pregnancy and childbirth, given the unique challenges I'm facing.

First and foremost, my primary sources of information have been my OB/GYN and the other healthcare providers on my prenatal care team. They've been instrumental in explaining the process, answering my questions, and guiding me through the various stages.

I've also done a lot of my own research online, looking into reputable medical websites and pregnancy resources. Things like WebMD, the Mayo Clinic, and baby-focused forums have been helpful for getting a general understanding of the experience.

Additionally, I've found a lot of value in connecting with other pregnant individuals, either through in-person support groups or online communities. Hearing firsthand experiences and coping strategies from people in similar situations has been really insightful.

My parents, who have been through pregnancy themselves, have also provided a lot of useful advice and perspective. And of course, my partner, Alex, has been an amazing resource, as we navigate this journey together.

I will say that with my complex medical history, I've had to be quite discerning about the information I consume. I try to focus on evidence-based, medically-sound sources, rather than relying too heavily on anecdotal or unverified claims.

Ultimately, I feel like I have a fairly comprehensive understanding of the pregnancy and childbirth process. But I know there's still a lot to learn, and I'm grateful for the support of my healthcare team and loved ones as I continue preparing for this new chapter.

Please let me know if you have any other questions about the resources I've utilized. I'm happy to provide more details.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*sighs slightly, a hint of concern in her voice* The financial aspects of this pregnancy and preparing for a baby have definitely been a source of stress and uncertainty for me.

As a college student, I don't have a lot of personal financial resources to draw from. I'm fortunate that my parents have been able to provide some support, but there are still significant out-of-pocket costs that have been challenging to manage.

My health insurance coverage has helped tremendously, but there have still been a number of expenses that have added up quickly - things like copays for prenatal visits, medications, tests, and potential hospital stays. It's been a constant juggling act trying to stay on top of it all.

I've also been trying to save up and prepare for the costs associated with having a newborn - things like baby supplies, childcare, and potential time off from school or work. It's been difficult to know exactly how much to budget for, but I'm doing my best to be proactive.

Thankfully, my partner Alex has also been contributing financially where they can, and we're trying to pool our resources as much as possible. But there's still a lot of uncertainty around the long-term financial implications of this pregnancy and raising a child.

I've tried to educate myself on available resources and assistance programs, like Medicaid, WIC, and local community organizations that may be able to provide support. But navigating all of those systems has been a challenge in itself.

Overall, the financial aspect has been one of the most stressful and anxiety-inducing parts of this experience for me. I'm doing my best to plan and prepare, but there's still a lot of unknown. I'm grateful for any help and guidance I can get.

Please let me know if you have any other questions about how I'm managing the financial side of this pregnancy and preparing for a baby. I'm happy to provide more details.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*pauses briefly, a pensive look on her face* The impact of my pregnancy on my work and employment situation has been a significant challenge that I'm still trying to navigate.

As a full-time college student, I don't have a traditional 9-to-5 job. But I do have various responsibilities and commitments that have been affected by my pregnancy.

For one, my course load and academic performance have suffered at times due to the physical and emotional toll of the pregnancy. There have been days where I've had to miss classes or reschedule exams because I was simply too ill or exhausted to attend.

I've tried to be upfront with my professors about my situation, and they've generally been understanding and accommodating. But it's still been a struggle to keep up with the demands of my studies while also managing my health.

Additionally, I've had to cut back on my part-time work at the campus library. The reduced hours and income have put an added financial strain on me and my family. It's been difficult to balance my medical needs with the need to earn money.

Looking ahead, I'm also very concerned about how I'll be able to continue my education and potentially find employment once the baby is born. Childcare costs, the potential need for time off, and the general demands of new parenthood are all weighing heavily on my mind.

I've been exploring options like taking a leave of absence, switching to part-time student status, or exploring online/remote learning opportunities. But the uncertainty is still quite daunting.

Overall, the pregnancy has had a significant impact on my work and academic life. I'm doing my best to adapt and find solutions, but it's been a constant source of stress and worry. Please let me know if you have any other questions about this aspect of my experience.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*nods thoughtfully* Yes, I've definitely been thinking a lot about the postpartum period and what happens after the baby arrives. It's something I've been trying to prepare for, even amidst all the other challenges of the pregnancy.

One of my biggest concerns is how I'll manage my own physical and mental health recovery while also caring for a newborn. Given my history of chronic pain, migraines, and mental health struggles, I know the postpartum period could be particularly challenging.

I've been working closely with my healthcare team to develop a plan for managing my medications, pain levels, and mental wellbeing in the weeks and months after delivery. They've emphasized the importance of having a strong support system in place.

To that end, my family and partner have committed to helping out as much as possible. My parents have offered to stay with me for the first few weeks to assist with things like feeding, diaper changes, and household tasks. And Alex has assured me they'll take time off work to be there as well.

I've also looked into local postpartum support groups and services that could provide additional resources and community. Things like lactation consultants, pelvic floor physical therapy, and mental health counseling are all on my radar.

Financially, we're still trying to figure out the best approach for childcare and any potential time off from school or work. It's an area of a lot of uncertainty and stress, but we're doing our best to prepare.

Overall, I feel like I have a decent plan in place, but I also know that the postpartum period can be incredibly unpredictable. I'm trying to stay flexible and open to adjusting as needed once the baby arrives. The health and wellbeing of myself and the baby are the top priorities.

Please let me know if you have any other questions about how I'm thinking about and preparing for the time after the birth. I'm happy to provide more details.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
*nods graciously* Thank you so much for the opportunity to share my story with you. I appreciate your empathy and professionalism in conducting this interview. Discussing the challenges and complexities of my pregnancy has been helpful for me, and I hope the information I provided will be useful for your research.

Please let me know if there's anything else I can do to assist you. I'm wishing you all the best in your important work. Take care.
